# Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models
## 1. Forward Diffusion Process
All vectors are column vectors. For multi-dimensional tensors, they can be flattened into column vectors.
In the forward process, we gradually transform a data distribution [math formula: P_0] into a distribution [math formula: P_T] which is close to [math formula: \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I})].
[math formula: x_0 \rightarrow x_1 \rightarrow x_2 \rightarrow x_3 \rightarrow ... \rightarrow x_T]
[math formula: P_0 \rightarrow P_1 \rightarrow P_2 \rightarrow P_3 \rightarrow ... \rightarrow P_T \approx \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I})]
[math formula: 
\mathbf{x}_0\sim{P_0}
]
Given noise schedule [math formula: (\beta_t)_{t=1}^T],
[math formula: 
\begin{align}
q(x_t|x_{t-1}) = \mathcal{N}(x_t; \sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1}, \beta_t\mathbf{I})
\end{align}
]
or equivalently, let [math formula: \alpha_t = 1 - \beta_t], we have
[math formula: 
\begin{align}
q(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}) = \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{x}_t; \sqrt{\alpha_t}\mathbf{x}_{t-1}, (1-\alpha_t)\mathbf{I})
\end{align}
]
### 1.1. Reparameterization
[math formula: 
x_t = \sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1}+\sqrt{\beta_t}\epsilon,\epsilon\sim\mathcal{N}(0,1)
]
By mathematical induction, we can prove that
[math formula: 
q(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_0) = \mathcal{N}(\mathbf{x}_t; \sqrt{\prod_{i=1}^{t}(1-\beta_i)}\mathbf{x}_0, (1-(\prod_{i=1}^{t}(1-\beta_i)))\mathbf{I})
]
That is, multiple noise additions can be expressed as one noise addition and it is easy to know that as the number of noise additions increases, the distribution of the data will be transformed into a standard normal distribution.
## 2. Training Process
Train a neural network [math formula: \mathbf{\epsilon}_{\theta}] to predict the noise [math formula: \mathbf{\epsilon}] in [math formula: \mathbf{x}_t = \sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t}\mathbf{x}_0 + \sqrt{1-\bar{\alpha}_t}\mathbf{\epsilon}]
To minimize:
[math formula: 
\begin{align}
\mathop{\mathbb{E}}\limits_{t, \mathbf{x}_0, \mathbf{\epsilon}} \left[ \left\| \mathbf{\epsilon} - \mathbf{\epsilon}_{\theta}(\mathbf{x}_t,t) \right\|^2 \right]
\end{align}
]
## 3. Sampling Process
First, estimate an clean data [math formula: \hat{\mathbf{x}}_0:=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t}}(\mathbf{x}_t - \sqrt{1-\bar{\alpha}_t}\mathbf{\epsilon}_{\theta}(\mathbf{x}_t,t))]
Then, we can use the following conditional distribution to sample [math formula: \mathbf{x}_{t-1}](the data at the previous time step):
[math formula: 
\begin{align}
q(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}|\mathbf{x}_t, \hat{\mathbf{x}}_0) &= \frac{q(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_{t-1}, \hat{\mathbf{x}}_0)q(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_0)}{q(\mathbf{x}_t|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_0)}\\
&=\frac{q(\mathbf{x}_t|\mathbf{x}_{t-1})q(\mathbf{x}_{t-1}|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_0)}{q(\mathbf{x}_t|\hat{\mathbf{x}}_0)}\\
&=\mathcal{N}\left( \boldsymbol{x}_{t-1}; \underbrace{\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})\boldsymbol{x}_t + \sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}(1-\alpha_t)\hat{\boldsymbol{x}}_0}{1-\bar{\alpha}_t}}_{\mu_q(\boldsymbol{x}_t, \hat{\boldsymbol{x}}_0)}, \underbrace{\frac{(1-\alpha_t)(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})}{1-\bar{\alpha}_t}\mathbf{I}}_{\Sigma_q(t)} \right)
\end{align}
]
In practice, [math formula: \Sigma_q(t)] is usually set to [math formula: \beta_t\mathbf{I}].
Substitute [math formula: \hat{\mathbf{x}}_0] into the formula above, we have
[math formula: 
\begin{align}
\mu_{q}  = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}} \mathbf{x}_t - \frac{1 - \alpha_t}{\sqrt{1 - \bar{\alpha}_t} \sqrt{\alpha_t}} \mathbf{\epsilon}_t
\end{align}
]
Therefore,
[math formula: 
\mathbf{x}_{t-1} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}} \left( \mathbf{x}_t - \frac{1-\alpha_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar{\alpha}_t}} \mathbf{\epsilon}_\theta(\mathbf{x}_t, t) \right) + \sqrt{(1-\alpha_t)}\mathbf{\epsilon}
]
## 4. Useful Formulas
[math formula: 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}_t = a_t\mathbf{x}_{t-1} + b_t\mathbf{\epsilon}_t
\end{align*}
]
By mathematical induction, we can prove that
[math formula: 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}_t &= (\prod_{i=1}^{t}a_i)\mathbf{x}_0 + \sum_{i=1}^{t}(\prod_{j=i+1}^{t}a_j)b_i\mathbf{\epsilon}_i
\end{align*}
]
If [math formula: a_t^2+b_t^2=1], then
[math formula: 
(\prod_{i=1}^{t}a_i)^2 + \sum_{i=1}^{t}(\prod_{j=i+1}^{t}a_j)^2b_i^2=1
]
Then
[math formula: 
\mathbf{x}_t = (\prod_{i=1}^{t}a_i)\mathbf{x}_0 + \sqrt{1-(\prod_{i=1}^{t}a_i)^2}\mathbf{\epsilon},\mathbf{\epsilon}\sim\mathcal{N}(\mathbf{0},\mathbf{I})
]
In particular, for DDPM, we have [math formula: a_t = \sqrt{\alpha_t} = \sqrt{1-\beta_t}] and [math formula: b_t = \sqrt{1-\alpha_t} = \sqrt{\beta_t}].
